<p class="lead">Runtime error 200</p>
<p>
An ancient DOS program crashed with the cryptic error message.
</p>
<p>
A runtime error 200 message usually occurs with old DOS applications written in Turbo and Borland Pascal. 
Turbo Pascal had a timing bug that caused its compiled programs to crash when they were executed on machines running at 200 MHz or faster. 
It is known as the <q>CRT unit issue</q> and can be fixed by applying a patch to the affected application. 
Otherwise, you can run the application in DOSBox, which can artificially slow down the speed of the emulated DOS session.
</p>
<p>
If you wish to patch the application we have created a guide to help you through it using the Windows Command Prompt.
</p>
<div class="container">
<ol class="list-group list-group-numbered">
  <li class="list-group-item d-flex justify-content-between align-items-start">
    <div class="ms-2 me-auto"><div class="fw-bold">Download <a href="/f/a43b6b">UNP 4.11</a></div>A Turbo Pascal decompression program.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="list-group-item d-flex justify-content-between align-items-start">
    <div class="ms-2 me-auto"><div class="fw-bold">Download <a href="/f/a33773">CRTFix 1.16</a></div>A CRT bug patching program.</div>
  </li>
  <li class="list-group-item d-flex justify-content-between align-items-start">
    <div class="ms-2 me-auto"><div class="fw-bold">Create a temporary directory</div>
    <code>> MKDIR C:\TPATCH</code></div>
  </li>
  <li class="list-group-item d-flex justify-content-between align-items-start">
    <div class="ms-2 me-auto"><div class="fw-bold">Unzip</div>Unzip both downloaded packages into the temporary directory.
    <br><code>> PKUNZIP TurboPascal-Unpack.zip C:\TPATCH<br>> PKUNZIP crtfix16.zip C:\TPATCH</code></div>
  </li>
  <li class="list-group-item d-flex justify-content-between align-items-start">
    <div class="ms-2 me-auto"><div class="fw-bold">Decompress</div>
    In our example, we are going to patch <code>defacto.exe</code>, which is the binary from an early Defacto magazine that suffers from this bug. 
    Use the UNP program to decompress the binary.
    <br><code>> UNP DEFACTO.EXE</code></div>
  </li>
  <li class="list-group-item d-flex justify-content-between align-items-start">
    <div class="ms-2 me-auto"><div class="fw-bold">Apply fix</div>
    Once the decompression is complete run the crtfix program to patch the binary.
    <br><code>> CRTFIX DEFACTO.EXE</code><br>
    That is it, if the crtfix returned a <q>Fixing code... Fixed</q> response then the binary is now patched and in future those annoying runtime error 200 messages should be gone.
    </div>
  </li>
</ol>
